body:
### Summary of the new feature / enhancement

Currently the compiler uses reflection to construct a generic instantiation of `PSVariableAssignmentBinder.CopyInstanceMembersOfValueType<T>`.  This method then unboxes with an explicit cast and then boxes that value.

The compiler could instead use `RuntimeHelpers.GetObjectValue` which is a method provided by the BCL specifically to enable dynamic languages to explicitly copy a boxed value type.

It's possible that it's slower though.  If that's the case a comment explaining why that method isn't used may be warranted.

### Proposed technical implementation details (optional)

Change [this code](https://github.com/PowerShell/PowerShell/blob/c49cf068b35bf71b0585efaa286df9f49b557805/src/System.Management.Automation/engine/runtime/Binding/Binders.cs#L1968-L1973) to something like the following:

```diff
--- a/src/System.Management.Automation/engine/runtime/Binding/Binders.cs
+++ b/src/System.Management.Automation/engine/runtime/Binding/Binders.cs
@@ -1968,1973 +1968,1972 @@
             if (s_mutableValueTypesWithInstanceMembers.ContainsKey(type))
             {
-                var genericMethodInfo = CachedReflectionInfo.PSVariableAssignmentBinder_CopyInstanceMembersOfValueType.MakeGenericMethod(new Type[] { type });
-                expr = Expression.Call(genericMethodInfo, convertedExpr, originalExpr);
+                expr = Expression.Call(CachedReflectionInfo.RuntimeHelpers_GetObjectValue, originalExpr)
                 needVersionCheck = false;
             }
```
